<DOC><DOCNO> AP890111-0238 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 0042EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   01-11 0524</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0545</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Reagan's advisers recommendedcurtailing deposit insurance for bank and savings and loan accounts,triggering swift negative reaction from Congress and the TreasuryDepartment.   In its final report to Reagan, the president's Council ofEconomic Advisers said Tuesday reducing protection for depositorswould encourage them to more closely monitor the institutionsholding their money.   But the Treasury Department, through Rep. Chalmers Wylie of Ohio,senior Republican on the House Banking Committee, promptly distanceditself from the latest proposal.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The incoming Bush administration gave ahigh-level advisory panel the go-ahead to begin work in earnest onforging a solution to the federal government's huge deficit problems.   Officials of the National Economic Commission said Tuesday theyhad received word from Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, who willstay on as the Bush administration's chief economic spokesman, thatBush will be looking for the panel's report March 1.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani has resignedafter a 5{-year tenure that saw several successful prosecutions ofinsider trading cases.   Giuliani, 44, said Monday he would leave the office before nextmonth.   Among Giuliani's targets on Wall Street was Dennis Levine, formermanaging director at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., who pleaded guiltyto securities fraud and other charges. That led to guilty pleas byfinancier Ivan Boesky and Drexel, among others.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A mistrial has been declared in the stockmanipulation case against GAF Corp. and a top company officer,throwing one of the biggest prosecutions spawned by the Wall Streetinsider trading scandal into confusion.   The mistrial ruling by U.S. District Judge Mary Johnson Lowe cameTuesday after the defense challenged the government prosecutor'shandling of an important piece of evidence and said it had unfairlyhurt their case.   Defense attorneys then requested dismissal of the entireindictment, but Lowe rejected their request and said she intended tobegin picking jurors for a new trial later in the week. The defenseattorneys said they would appeal her decision to the 2nd CircuitCourt of Appeals.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   TW Services Inc. has rejected an offer byConiston Partners to ease the conditions on Coniston's $1.4 billionbid for the food services company.   TW Services said Tuesday its chairman, Frank L. Salizzoni, sent aletter to the New York-based investment firm, refusing to take anyaction on the company's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover defense andrefusing to waive a requirement that a takeover must be approved bythe TW Services board.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   One of the nation's largest banks agreed to paya record $14 million in back pay to women and minorities it employedfrom 1973 to 1988, but refused to concede that it had discriminated.   Harris Trust and Savings Bank of Chicago, 40th among the nation'sbanks in assets last year, said Tuesday it agreed to settle chargesoriginally filed by the Labor Department in 1977 to avoid ``morelegal and statistical wrangling.'' A Chicago group that hadsupported the government's complaint said up to 5,000 people couldshare in the award.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>